			<subsubsection><title> First-Order Equations </title>

				<p>
					First-order linear homogeneous constant coefficient (LHCC) equations are the simplest case of LHCC differential equations. 
					These equations involve only the first derivative of the unknown function and a constant coefficient. Despite their simplicity, 
					they provide an important foundation for solving higher-order LHCC equations.
				</p>

				<paragraphs><title> The General Form </title>

					<p>
						A first-order LHCC equation has the general form:
					</p>

					<men xml:id="first-order-lhcc">
						a_1 y' + a_0 y = 0,
					</men>

					<p>
						where <m>a_1</m> and <m>a_0</m> are constants, with <m>a_1 \neq 0</m> to ensure the equation is truly first-order. 
						Our goal is to determine the general solution for <m>y(x)</m>.
					</p>

				</paragraphs>

				<paragraphs><title> Solving First-Order LHCC Equations </title>

					<p>
						To solve equation <xref ref="first-order-lhcc"/>, we assume an exponential solution of the form:
					</p>

					<me>
						y = e^{rx}.
					</me>

					<p>
						Differentiating this expression gives:
					</p>

					<me>
						y' = r e^{rx}.
					</me>

					<p>
						Substituting these into <xref ref="first-order-lhcc"/> results in:
					</p>

					<me>
						a_1 r e^{rx} + a_0 e^{rx} = 0.
					</me>

					<p>
						Factoring out <m>e^{rx}</m> (which is never zero) leads to the characteristic equation:
					</p>

					<me xml:id="first-order-characteristic">
						a_1 r + a_0 = 0.
					</me>

					<p>
						Solving for <m>r</m>, we find:
					</p>

					<me>
						r = -\frac{a_0}{a_1}.
					</me>

					<p>
						Thus, the general solution to the first-order equation is:
					</p>

					<me>
						y = c e^{-\frac{a_0}{a_1} x},
					</me>

					<p>
						where <m>c</m> is an arbitrary constant.
					</p>

