						<men>
							y'' - 5y' + 6y = 0.
						</men>

						<p>
							The characteristic equation is:
						</p>

						<me>
							r^2 - 5r + 6 = 0.
						</me>

						<p>
							Factoring:
						</p>

						<me>
							(r - 2)(r - 3) = 0.
						</me>

						<p>
							This gives the roots <m>r_1 = 2</m> and <m>r_2 = 3</m>, so the general solution is:
						</p>

						<me>
							y = c_1 e^{2x} + c_2 e^{3x}.
						</me>

					</example>

				</paragraphs>

				<paragraphs><title> Case 2: Repeated Real Roots </title>

					<p>
						If the characteristic equation has a single repeated root <m>r</m>, meaning:
					</p>

					<me>
						a_2 r^2 + a_1 r + a_0 = (r - r_0)^2 = 0,
					</me>

					<p>
						then there is only one exponential solution <m>e^{r_0 x}</m>. To obtain a second independent solution, we use the method of reduction of order, 
						which leads to the general solution:
					</p>

					<me>
						y = c_1 e^{r_0 x} + c_2 x e^{r_0 x}.
					</me>

					<example><title> Example: Solving with Repeated Roots </title>

						<p>
							Solve the equation:
						</p>

						<men>
							y'' - 4y' + 4y = 0.
						</men>

						<p>
							The characteristic equation is:
						</p>

						<me>
							r^2 - 4r + 4 = 0.
						</me>

						<p>
							Factoring:
						</p>

						<me>
							(r - 2)^2 = 0.
						</me>

						<p>
							This gives a repeated root <m>r_0 = 2</m>, so the general solution is:
						</p>

						<me>
							y = c_1 e^{2x} + c_2 x e^{2x}.
						</me>

					</example>

				</paragraphs>

				<paragraphs><title> Case 3: Complex Conjugate Roots </title>

					<p>
						If the characteristic equation has complex conjugate roots:
					</p>

					<me>
						r = \alpha \pm i\beta,
					</me>

					<p>
						then using Euler's formula:
					</p>

					<me>
						e^{i\beta x} = \cos(\beta x) + i\sin(\beta x),
					</me>

					<p>
						we express the general solution in terms of real functions:
					</p>

					<me>
						y = e^{\alpha x} (c_1 \cos(\beta x) + c_2 \sin(\beta x)).
					</me>

					<example><title> Example: Solving with Complex Roots </title>

						<p>
							Solve the equation:
						</p>

						<men>
							y'' + y = 0.
						</men>

						<p>
							The characteristic equation is:
						</p>

						<me>
							r^2 + 1 = 0.
						</me>

						<p>
							Solving for <m>r</m>:
						</p>

						<me>
							r = \pm i.
						</me>

						<p>
							Since <m>\alpha = 0</m> and <m>\beta = 1</m>, the general solution is:
						</p>

						<me>
							y = c_1 \cos x + c_2 \sin x.
						</me>

					</example>

				</paragraphs>

				<paragraphs><title> Summary of Root Types and Solution Forms </title>

					<p>
						The table below summarizes how different types of roots affect the solution to a second-order LHCC equation:
					</p>

					<table>
						<row>
							<entry><b>Root Type</b></entry>
							<entry><b>General Solution</b></entry>
						</row>
						<row>
							<entry> Distinct real roots <m>r_1, r_2</m> </entry>
							<entry> <m>y = c_1 e^{r_1 x} + c_2 e^{r_2 x}</m> </entry>
						</row>
						<row>
							<entry> Repeated real root <m>r_0</m> </entry>
							<entry> <m>y = c_1 e^{r_0 x} + c_2 x e^{r_0 x}</m> </entry>
						</row>
						<row>
							<entry> Complex conjugate roots <m>\alpha \pm i\beta</m> </entry>
							<entry> <m>y = e^{\alpha x} (c_1 \cos(\beta x) + c_2 \sin(\beta x))</m> </entry>
						</row>
					</table>

				</paragraphs>

				<outcomes><title> Key Takeaways </title>
					<ul>
						<li> The nature of the characteristic equation's roots determines the form of the general solution.</li>
						<li> Distinct real roots correspond to simple exponential solutions.</li>
						<li> Repeated roots require an additional polynomial factor.</li>
						<li> Complex roots lead to oscillatory solutions involving sine and cosine.</li>
					</ul>
				</outcomes>

			</subsubsection>

		</subsection>

		<subsection><title> Higher-Order Equations </title>

			<introduction>
				<p>
					While first- and second-order LHCC equations provide useful insights, real-world problems often involve 
					higher-order differential equations. These equations, which include third-order, fourth-order, and beyond, 
					follow the same fundamental principles but introduce additional complexity in their characteristic equations.
				</p>

				<p>
					In this subsection, we extend our solution techniques to higher-order LHCC equations. We will analyze the 
					general structure of these equations, explain how to construct and solve their characteristic equations, 
					and examine how different types of characteristic roots influence the form of the solution.
				</p>

				<p>
					Understanding higher-order LHCC equations is essential for applications in physics, engineering, and applied mathematics, 
					where such equations frequently arise in modeling oscillatory systems, mechanical structures, and electrical circuits.
				</p>
			</introduction>

			<subsubsection><title> General Form of Higher-Order LHCC Equations </title>

				<p>
					So far, we have studied first- and second-order linear homogeneous constant coefficient (LHCC) equations. 
					Now, we extend these ideas to higher-order equations, which follow the same fundamental structure but involve additional derivatives. 
					In this section, we explore the general form of higher-order LHCC equations and why their solutions still involve exponentials.
				</p>

				<paragraphs><title> The General Form </title>

					<p>
						A general <m>n</m>-th order linear homogeneous constant coefficient (LHCC) equation takes the form:
					</p>

					<men xml:id="higher-order-lhcc">
						a_n y^{(n)} + a_{n-1} y^{(n-1)} + \cdots + a_1 y' + a_0 y = 0,
					</men>

					<p>
						where <m>a_n, a_{n-1}, \dots, a_1, a_0</m> are constant coefficients, and <m>y^{(n)}</m> represents the <m>n</m>-th derivative of <m>y</m>. 
						Our goal is to determine the general solution for <m>y(x)</m>.
					</p>

					<p>
						As in the second-order case, the key to solving this equation is to find functions whose derivatives satisfy a similar structure. 
						We will see that, once again, exponential functions provide the fundamental solutions.
					</p>

				</paragraphs>

				<paragraphs><title> Why Exponentials Still Work </title>

					<p>
						To solve a higher-order LHCC equation, we assume an exponential solution of the form:
					</p>

					<me>
						y = e^{rx}.
					</me>

					<p>
						Differentiating this function multiple times gives:
					</p>

					<md>
						<mrow> y' = r e^{rx}, </mrow>
						<mrow> y'' = r^2 e^{rx}, </mrow>
						<mrow> y^{(n)} = r^n e^{rx}. </mrow>
					</md>

					<p>
						Substituting these expressions into equation <xref ref="higher-order-lhcc"/> results in:
					</p>

					<me>
						a_n r^n e^{rx} + a_{n-1} r^{n-1} e^{rx} + \cdots + a_1 r e^{rx} + a_0 e^{rx} = 0.
					</me>

					<p>
						Factoring out <m>e^{rx}</m>, we obtain the characteristic equation:
					</p>

					<me xml:id="higher-order-characteristic">
						a_n r^n + a_{n-1} r^{n-1} + \cdots + a_1 r + a_0 = 0.
					</me>

					<p>
						This equation, a polynomial in <m>r</m> of degree <m>n</m>, determines the values of <m>r</m> that lead to valid exponential solutions. 
						The solutions of this characteristic equation dictate the fundamental solution set for <xref ref="higher-order-lhcc"/>.
					</p>

				</paragraphs>

				<paragraphs><title> The General Solution for Higher Orders </title>

					<p>
						Since the characteristic equation is a polynomial of degree <m>n</m>, it has <m>n</m> roots (real or complex). 
						The general solution depends on the nature of these roots:
					</p>

					<ul>
						<li> If all roots are distinct and real, the solution consists of <m>n</m> independent exponential terms.</li>
						<li> If there are repeated roots, additional polynomial factors appear.</li>
						<li> If there are complex conjugate roots, the solution involves sine and cosine functions.</li>
					</ul>

					<p>
						More formally, if the characteristic equation has roots <m>r_1, r_2, \dots, r_n</m>, then the general solution takes the form:
					</p>

					<me>
						y = c_1 e^{r_1 x} + c_2 e^{r_2 x} + \dots + c_n e^{r_n x}.
					</me>

					<p>
						If a root <m>r</m> has multiplicity <m>m</m>, then the solution includes additional polynomial terms:
					</p>

					<me>
						y = (c_1 + c_2 x + \dots + c_m x^{m-1}) e^{r x}.
					</me>

					<p>
						If the characteristic equation has complex conjugate roots <m>\alpha \pm i\beta</m>, the solution is written as:
					</p>

					<me>
						y = e^{\alpha x} (c_1 \cos(\beta x) + c_2 \sin(\beta x)).
					</me>

					<p>
						The number of independent solutions always matches the order of the differential equation, ensuring that the general solution captures all possible behaviors.
					</p>

				</paragraphs>

				<paragraphs><title> Example: A Third-Order LHCC Equation </title>

					<example><title> Solving a Third-Order LHCC Equation </title>

						<p>
							Consider the third-order equation:
						</p>

						<men>
							y''' - 4y'' + 5y' - 2y = 0.
						</men>

						<p>
							The characteristic equation is:
						</p>

						<me>
							r^3 - 4r^2 + 5r - 2 = 0.
						</me>

						<p>
							Factoring, we find:
						</p>

						<me>
							(r - 1)(r - 2)(r - 1) = 0.
						</me>

						<p>
							This gives the roots <m>r_1 = 1</m> (repeated) and <m>r_2 = 2</m>. Since <m>r_1</m> is a repeated root, the general solution takes the form:
						</p>

						<me>
							y = c_1 e^{x} + c_2 x e^{x} + c_3 e^{2x}.
						</me>

					</example>

				</paragraphs>

				<outcomes><title> Key Takeaways </title>
					<ul>
						<li> Higher-order LHCC equations follow the same principles as second-order ones, with solutions determined by the characteristic equation.</li>
						<li> The characteristic equation is an <m>n</m>-th degree polynomial whose roots determine the independent solutions.</li>
						<li> Exponential functions still form the basis of solutions, with polynomial factors appearing for repeated roots and sine/cosine terms for complex roots.</li>
						<li> The number of independent solutions matches the order of the differential equation.</li>
					</ul>
				</outcomes>

				<p>
					Now that we understand the general structure of higher-order LHCC equations, the next step is to explore specific cases and techniques for solving them efficiently.
				</p>

			</subsubsection>

			<subsubsection><title> Solving the Characteristic Equation </title>

				<p>
					In the previous section, we derived the characteristic equation, which determines the fundamental solutions of higher-order LHCC equations.
					However, solving this polynomial equation can be challenging, especially as the order of the differential equation increases.
					In this section, we explore the difficulties of solving higher-degree polynomials, discuss special cases where solutions are easier to find,
					and introduce modern technological tools that can assist in solving characteristic equations efficiently.
				</p>

				<paragraphs><title> Challenges in Solving Higher-Degree Polynomials </title>

					<p>
						The characteristic equation for an <m>n</m>-th order LHCC equation is an <m>n</m>-th degree polynomial:
					</p>

					<me xml:id="general-characteristic">
						a_n r^n + a_{n-1} r^{n-1} + \dots + a_1 r + a_0 = 0.
					</me>

					<p>
						While solving quadratic (<m>n=2</m>) characteristic equations is straightforward using the quadratic formula, higher-degree equations introduce significant challenges:
					</p>

					<ul>
						<li> <em>Cubic and quartic equations</em> (<m>n=3</m> or <m>n=4</m>) have general formulas, but they are complex and rarely used in practice.</li>
						<li> <em>Polynomial equations of degree five or higher</em> (<m>n \geq 5</m>) generally cannot be solved using a formula (Abel-Ruffini theorem).</li>
						<li> <em>Factoring becomes difficult</em> as the number of possible rational roots increases.</li>
						<li> <em>Complex and repeated roots require additional algebraic manipulation</em>, making hand calculations cumbersome.</li>
					</ul>

					<p>
						In many cases, direct algebraic methods are impractical for finding exact solutions, necessitating alternative approaches.
					</p>

				</paragraphs>

				<paragraphs><title> Special Cases That Simplify Solutions </title>

					<p>
						Despite these challenges, some characteristic equations can be solved more easily if they fall into special cases. These include:
					</p>

					<ul>
						<li> <em>Quadratic Polynomials:</em> The quadratic formula provides an explicit solution for <m>n=2</m>: 
							<me>
								r = \frac{-a_1 \pm \sqrt{a_1^2 - 4a_0 a_2}}{2a_2}.
							</me>
						</li>
						<li> <em>Rational Roots:</em> If the coefficients are integers, the <em>rational root theorem</em> helps identify possible rational solutions.</li>
						<li> <em>Factoring by Inspection:</em> Some polynomials can be factored directly, especially when they have simple integer roots.</li>
						<li> <em>Repeated Roots:</em> When a root appears multiple times, recognizing it allows for polynomial reduction.</li>
						<li> <em>Complex Conjugate Roots:</em> For equations with real coefficients, complex roots always appear in conjugate pairs <m>(\alpha \pm i\beta)</m>, reducing the number of unknowns.</li>
					</ul>

					<example><title> Factoring a Simple Cubic Polynomial </title>

						<p>
							Solve the characteristic equation:
						</p>

						<me>
							r^3 - 6r^2 + 11r - 6 = 0.
						</me>

						<solution>
							<p>
								Using the rational root theorem, we test integer factors of <m>-6</m>: <m>\pm 1, \pm 2, \pm 3, \pm 6</m>. 
								Substituting <m>r = 1</m>, we get:
							</p>

							<me>
								(1)^3 - 6(1)^2 + 11(1) - 6 = 0.
							</me>

							<p>
								Since <m>r = 1</m> is a root, we factor <m>(r - 1)</m> from the polynomial using polynomial division:
							</p>

							<me>
								(r - 1)(r^2 - 5r + 6) = 0.
							</me>

							<p>
								Factoring the quadratic term:
							</p>

							<me>
								(r - 1)(r - 2)(r - 3) = 0.
							</me>

							<p>
								Thus, the roots are <m>r = 1, 2, 3</m>, and the general solution is:
							</p>

							<me>
								y = c_1 e^x + c_2 e^{2x} + c_3 e^{3x}.
							</me>

						</solution>

					</example>

				</paragraphs>

				<paragraphs><title> Using Technology to Solve Characteristic Equations </title>

					<p>
						For characteristic equations that are difficult to solve by hand, technology provides powerful tools for finding exact or approximate roots.
						Some commonly used methods include:
					</p>

					<ul>
						<li> <em>Graphing Calculators</em>: Graphing the polynomial function <m>f(r)</m> allows for visual identification of roots.</li>
						<li> <em>Symbolic Algebra Systems (CAS)</em>: Software such as Wolfram Alpha, MATLAB, and Mathematica can factor and solve polynomials symbolically.</li>
						<li> <em>Numerical Methods</em>: Techniques like Newton's method or root-finding algorithms can approximate solutions when exact solutions are impossible.</li>
						<li> <em>Python Libraries</em>: Libraries like NumPy and SymPy can quickly compute polynomial roots.</li>
					</ul>

					<example><title> Using Python to Solve a Fourth-Degree Polynomial </title>

						<p>
							Solve the characteristic equation:
						</p>

						<me>
							r^4 - 3r^3 + 2r^2 - r + 1 = 0.
						</me>

						<solution>
							<p>
								Using Python's NumPy library, we execute:
							</p>

							<codeblock>
							import numpy as np
							roots = np.roots([1, -3, 2, -1, 1])
							print(roots)
							</codeblock>

							<p>
								The output gives:
							</p>

							<me>
								r_1 = 2, \quad r_2 \approx 0.618, \quad r_3, r_4 \approx -0.809 \pm i 0.588.
							</me>

							<p>
								The general solution is then:
							</p>

							<me>
								y = c_1 e^{2x} + c_2 e^{0.618x} + e^{-0.809x} (c_3 \cos(0.588x) + c_4 \sin(0.588x)).
							</me>

						</solution>

					</example>

				</paragraphs>

				<outcomes><title> Key Takeaways </title>
					<ul>
						<li> Higher-degree characteristic equations can be difficult to solve algebraically, especially for <m>n \geq 5</m>.</li>
						<li> Special cases, such as factorable polynomials and rational roots, can simplify finding solutions.</li>
						<li> Modern technology, including graphing tools, CAS software, and numerical methods, provides efficient ways to solve characteristic equations.</li>
						<li> Approximations may be necessary for equations with irrational or complex roots.</li>
					</ul>
				</outcomes>

				<p>
					Having explored strategies for solving the characteristic equation, we now turn our attention to understanding how initial conditions determine unique solutions for LHCC equations.
				</p>

			</subsubsection>

			<subsubsection><title> Examples of Solving Higher-Order LHCC Equations </title>

				<p>
					In this section, we apply the methods developed in previous sections to solve concrete examples of higher-order linear homogeneous constant coefficient (LHCC) differential equations. By working through these examples step by step, we will reinforce the key concepts, including the use of the characteristic equation and the interpretation of different root types.
				</p>

				<paragraphs><title> Example 1: Third-Order Equation with Distinct Real Roots </title>

					<example><title> Solving a Third-Order LHCC Equation </title>

						<p>
							Consider the third-order differential equation:
						</p>

						<men>
							y''' - 6y'' + 11y' - 6y = 0.
						</men>

						<p>
							We begin by finding the characteristic equation:
						</p>

						<me>
							r^3 - 6r^2 + 11r - 6 = 0.
						</me>

						<p>
							Factoring the polynomial:
						</p>

						<me>
							(r - 1)(r - 2)(r - 3) = 0.
						</me>

						<p>
							This gives the distinct real roots <m>r = 1, 2, 3</m>. Thus, the general solution is:
						</p>

						<me>
							y = c_1 e^x + c_2 e^{2x} + c_3 e^{3x}.
						</me>

						<p>
							This solution consists of a linear combination of exponential terms, each corresponding to a root of the characteristic equation.
						</p>

					</example>

				</paragraphs>

				<paragraphs><title> Example 2: Fourth-Order Equation with a Repeated Root </title>

					<example><title> Solving a Fourth-Order LHCC Equation with a Repeated Root </title>

						<p>
							Consider the fourth-order equation:
						</p>

						<men>
							y'''' - 4y''' + 6y'' - 4y' + y = 0.
						</men>

						<p>
							The characteristic equation is:
						</p>

						<me>
							r^4 - 4r^3 + 6r^2 - 4r + 1 = 0.
						</me>

						<p>
							Factoring, we obtain:
						</p>

						<me>
							(r - 1)^4 = 0.
						</me>

						<p>
							Since <m>r = 1</m> is a root of multiplicity 4, we must include polynomial factors in the solution. The general solution is:
						</p>

						<me>
							y = (c_1 + c_2 x + c_3 x^2 + c_4 x^3) e^x.
						</me>

						<p>
							This accounts for the repeated root by introducing additional polynomial terms in <m>x</m>.
						</p>

					</example>

				</paragraphs>

				<paragraphs><title> Example 3: Third-Order Equation with Complex Roots </title>

					<example><title> Solving an LHCC Equation with Complex Roots </title>

						<p>
							Consider the third-order equation:
						</p>

						<men>
							y''' + y' + y = 0.
						</men>

						<p>
							The characteristic equation is:
						</p>

						<me>
							r^3 + r + 1 = 0.
						</me>

						<p>
							This equation has one real root and two complex conjugate roots. Using numerical or algebraic methods, we find:
						</p>

						<me>
							r_1 = -1, \quad r_2,3 = \frac{1}{2} \pm i \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}.
						</me>

						<p>
							The general solution is then:
						</p>

						<me>
							y = c_1 e^{-x} + e^{\frac{1}{2}x} (c_2 \cos(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} x) + c_3 \sin(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} x)).
						</me>

						<p>
							This form arises because complex conjugate roots lead to solutions involving sine and cosine terms, modulated by an exponential factor.
						</p>

					</example>

				</paragraphs>

				<outcomes><title> Key Takeaways </title>
					<ul>
						<li> The characteristic equation provides the key to solving LHCC differential equations.</li>
						<li> Distinct real roots correspond to exponential solutions of the form <m>e^{r x}</m>.</li>
						<li> Repeated roots introduce polynomial factors <m>x^k</m> to maintain independent solutions.</li>
						<li> Complex roots yield solutions involving sine and cosine functions with an exponential term.</li>
					</ul>
				</outcomes>

				<p>
					These examples illustrate the key solution methods for higher-order LHCC equations. With these techniques, we can systematically solve any such equation given its characteristic equation.
				</p>

			</subsubsection>

